The functions of the third extended to the expulsion of evil spirits by the imposition of hands upon persons possessed, recently baptized, and catechumens. The ceremony was

always aceompanied with aspersion, and the name benett was doubtless taken from the aqua benedicta, ectu benite, or, perhaps, from the vessel called in Freneh Minister, which contained the hely-water. In a will dated 1449 is a bequest of “a gret holy-water scoppe of silver, with a staff benature, the sayd benature and staff weying xx nobles in plate.'' The staff benature was the aspersorium, termed in the Promptorium STRENKYL, halywater styc. Fox, relating the death of Hooper, states that it was part of the cere- mony of degrading Bishops to ‘⁶ take from them the lowest vesture which they had in taking bennet and collet’' (i. e. acolyte). Eecles. Hist. iii. 152, A.D. 1555. Τ.
